The contraction hierarchies (CH) algorithm is a two-phase approach to the shortest path problem consisting of a preprocessing phase and a query phase. As road networks change rather infrequently, more time (seconds to hours) can be used to once precompute some calculations before queries are to be answered. Using this precomputed data, many queries can be answered taking very little time (microseconds) each.[1][3] CHs rely on shortcuts to achieve this speedup. A shortcut connects two vertices 



        u


    {\displaystyle u}

 and 



        v


    {\displaystyle v}

 not adjacent in the original graph. Its edge weight is the sum of the edge weights on the shortest 



        u


    {\displaystyle u}

-



        v


    {\displaystyle v}

 path.

